<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hick; Randy Lewis, ; Mimi Ko 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 DAY FOR AFRICA: Carl Burrowes of Fullerton likes to pull this quiz on people: 
Name another country that has a red, white and blue flag and celebrates its 
independence day in July. It's his native Liberia, Africa's oldest republic at 
147 years old. . . . More than 200 Liberians who live here now will celebrate 
the event today at William R. Mason Regional Park in Irvine. Burrowes says 
entertainment will include soccer for the adults and Liberian folk tales for 
the children. 
</P>
<P>
 CAR CITY: The Saturn Corp. promotes the notion that Saturn car owners are one 
big happy family. More than 8,000 Saturn owners have purchased $16 discount 
tickets to spend today at Knott's Berry Farm. Included is a picnic lunch, a 
T-shirt and a preview of the 1995 Saturn. . . . One sticky question: If you're 
one of 8,200, how do you find your car in the parking lot? "By paying very 
careful attention where you park," says Knott's spokesman Bob Ochsner. 
</P>
<P>
 EARLY OPERA: One tiny fear about tonight's gala preview of "Phantom of the 
Opera" at the Orange County Performing Arts Center in Costa Mesa: That regular 
patrons used to its usual 8 p.m. starting time will miss the first act. 
"Phantom" -- tonight only -- starts at 7. (Sunday's opening is at 7:30, and all 
performances after that start at 8). . . . South Coast Plaza Village's six 
restaurants will join in on the hoopla: They'll provide free shuttle service on 
weekends for ticket holders, to save on parking hassles at the center. 
</P>
<P>
 NO REAL PIONEERS: Maybe the California Angels aren't having the kind of season 
they want. But they're doing better than the other baseball team that shares 
Anaheim Stadium with them -- the Pioneers. That's the name of the fictional, 
losing American League West baseball team on the sitcom "Hardball," which is 
unveiled on Fox TV this fall. Why did they choose Anaheim Stadium? Producers 
say it was cheaper to rent than Dodger Stadium and less instantly identifiable. 
The losing team, they are quick to add, was not modeled after the Angels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
