651 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
JUDGE REJECTS BID TO DELAY LEGAL CASE OVER LANDFILL; COURTS: PROPONENTS OF 
WELDON CANYON DUMP WANTED TO POSTPONE DECISION UNTIL AFTER NOVEMBER ELECTION. 
HEARING IS SET FOR AUG. 22. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PHYLLIS W. JORDAN, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The legal case against the Weldon Canyon landfill initiative will be argued 
before a judge in one month, giving the courts a chance to settle the matter 
before it goes to Ventura County voters in November. 
</P>
<P>
 In a hearing Friday, retired Appeals Judge Richard W. Abbe rejected a move by 
landfill proponents to delay the decision until after the election. Instead, he 
set a court date for Aug. 22. 
</P>
<P>
 "I believe this matter should go forward," Abbe said. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials opposed to the initiative, which would ask voters to approve zoning 
and land-use rights for a landfill, said the expedited schedule was essential 
to their case. 
</P>
<P>
 "It is very, very important to the county that this matter be heard and 
determined by the end of August," Assistant County Counsel William Moritz told 
the judge. That would leave time for appeals before the county prints its 
ballots for November. 
</P>
<P>
 "The initiative in our view asks the voters to pass a law that would be 
unconstitutional," Moritz said. The county is expected to support the lawsuit 
filed by the Ojai and Ventura city councils. 
</P>
<P>
 Backers of the landfill said the schedule would leave them little time to 
prepare a case. And it could deny voters a chance to speak on the matter, they 
argued. Residents throughout the county signed petitions this spring, putting 
the Weldon Canyon matter to a vote of the people. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're dealing with a constitutional right," said Wes Peltzeran attorney 
representing supporters. "It's up to the voters to decide." 
</P>
<P>
 Peltzer also argued that the judge should add Taconic Resources, the San Diego 
County partnership pushing the ballot initiative, to the lawsuit. Currently, 
the suit names only Eloise Brown, the Moorpark activist who started the 
petition drive. 
</P>
<P>
 Abbe refused to add Taconic, saying it would only delay the case. 
</P>
<P>
 Abbe, a retired justice on the 2nd District Court of Appeals, was picked for 
the case after five Ventura County judges removed themselves or were 
disqualified from hearing the politically divisive matter. 
</P>
<P>
 The landfill issue pits communities in the western half of the county against 
neighbors to the east. Fearing that the west county will begin shipping its 
trash to the Simi Valley Landfill, many east county residents want to see a 
site developed in the west. 
</P>
<P>
 A plan for Weldon Canyon was dropped last summer when it became clear that the 
Board of Supervisors would not approve it. A new group, Taconic Resources, is 
asking the voters to grant the needed approval for the project. 
</P>
<P>
 Abbe said he was unaware of the political machinations surrounding Weldon 
Canyon. 
</P>
<P>
 "I saw a bumper sticker on the way in that says 'Dump Weldon.' I don't know 
what that means," he told the lawyers assembled before him. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't know anything about Ventura County," he said. "I live in Santa 
Barbara County. I like it down here, though. I'd hate to see it covered with 
trash." 
</P>
<P>
 The issues before him in next month's hearing will focus on the legality of 
the ballot initiative. Lawyers for Ojai and Ventura argue that the measure 
violates the law in at least a dozen ways. Chiefly, they say an initiative 
cannot be used to grant land-use rights to a specific company. 
</P>
<P>
 Peltzer and Taconic officials say the measure is legally defensible and should 
go to the voters in November. Peltzer said a similar case, involving a ballot 
initiative and land-use rights, is coming before the state Supreme Court this 
fall. 
</P>
<P>
 The judge should wait for a decision in that matter before ruling on the 
Ventura case, Peltzer argued. "There just isn't any reason not to allow the 
voters to vote on this," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Abbe rejected that reasoning and set a four-week schedule for filing briefs 
and preparing arguments. The county has not officially joined the suit, but is 
expected to file a brief in support of the Ojai and Ventura suit. 
</P>
<P>
 Three of five supervisors oppose the measure, and the county counsel has 
declared it legally invalid. 
</P>
