<HEADLINE>
<P>
BENEFIT WILL AID REFUGEES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICK VANDERKNYFF, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After a couple of quiet years, the UC Irvine students behind Project Ngoc have 
brought back their annual fund-raiser in a big way. 
</P>
<P>
 Project Ngoc was founded on the campus in 1987 to assist Southeast Asian 
refugee camps by sending money and volunteers. During the project's first 
years, annual summer benefits featured mostly student talent in campus 
theaters. 
</P>
<P>
 But this summer the group has booked some of the top entertainers in Little 
Saigon and will mount the show in the upscale Irvine Barclay Theatre. The show, 
Sunday at 2 p.m., will feature about 15 pop singers, including Cong Thanh, 
Lynn, Phuong Hong Que and Don Ho (not to be confused with the Hawaiian Don Ho), 
doing two songs each with a house band. 
</P>
<P>
 Also on the program: traditional Vietnamese music and dance, along with 
acrobatics and a short drama performed by the group Club O'Noodles. The show 
will be hosted by Viet Dzung and Minh Phuong, disc jockeys with Little Saigon 
Radio. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're trying to revive the tradition (and) we're trying to take it to another 
level," said Tuan Ho, a UCI graduate directing the event's organizing 
committee. "This time," he noted, "we have all professional singers." 
</P>
<P>
 Ho estimates that the show could raise more than $10,000. All the performers 
are donating their time and all proceeds will benefit Project Ngoc, which was 
named for a Vietnamese boat person killed by Thai pirates. 
</P>
<P>
 The main purpose of the show, though, is to "spread awareness of the refugee 
issue," Ho said. The camps are scheduled to close in the next year, and 
remaining refugees are to be returned to their countries, which is one reason 
the organizers decided to make this year's show more ambitious than usual. 
</P>
<P>
 Ho said only single seats remain on the theater's main level but that tickets 
to the balcony will be available at the door. 
</P>
<P>
 * A benefit for Project Ngoc takes place Sunday at 2 p.m. at the Irvine 
Barclay Theatre, 4242 Campus Drive, Irvine. $15 to $25; $12 for students. (714) 
854-4646.  
</P>
</TEXT>
