</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAYE CLARK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The choir at the United Methodist Church of Garden Grove will give a concert 
Sunday then leaves Tuesday for their Canadian tour. The choir usually tours 
every three years and will perform in Halifax, Charlottetown, Fredericton, 
Quebec City, Ottawa and Stratford. Raymond Woods directs the choir. 
</P>
<P>
 A free-will offering will be taken for the 4 p.m. concert at 12741 Main St. 
Information: (714) 534-1070. 
</P>
<P>
 The Aldersgate Chorale at the First United Methodist Church of Fullerton will 
present "An Evening of Walt Disney" during an Ice Cream Social tonight and 
Sunday at 6:30. 
</P>
<P>
 Tickets are $5 for adults, $2 for children ages 5 to 10, ages 4 and under are 
free. The church is at 114 N. Pomona Ave. Information: (714) 871-4115. 
</P>
<P>
 Irvine's South Coast Community Church is offering a Wednesday series of 
dinners and speakers. Humorist and Spatula Ministries' founder Barbara Johnson 
will speak during the program on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
 The dinner is at 5:30 followed by worship and program at 7. Tickets for the 
dinners are $7 for adults, $2.50 for children. Those who would like to bring 
their own dinners are welcome to do so. The church is at 5120 Bonita Canyon 
Drive. Information: (714) 854-7600. 
</P>
<P>
 "Soul Searching in the Material World" is the Rev. Chris Schriner's topic as 
guest speaker Sunday at the Orange Coast Unitarian Universalist Church in Costa 
Mesa. He is minister of the Unitarian Universalist Fellowship of Laguna Beach 
and is also a psychotherapist and author. 
</P>
<P>
 The service is at 10:30 a.m. at 1259 Victoria St. Information: (714) 646-4652. 
</P>
<P>
 Associate Pastor Martha Lynne Austin of Aldersgate United Methodist Church of 
Tustin recently received her master of divinity degree from the School of 
Theology at Claremont. She also is the recipient of the Wilshire Preaching 
Award, which is provided by the Wilshire United Methodist Church for the 
student "whose performance in preaching class is most exemplary of the 
excellence required for effective church leadership." 
</P>
<P>
 The School of Theology at Claremont is a seminary of the United Methodist 
Church whose graduates serve in many countries. Information: (909) 626-3521. 
</P>
<P>
 The one-week Vacation Bible School at Laguna Niguel Presbyterian Church USA 
begins Monday and meets from 9 to 11:45 a.m. and is for children ages 4 through 
fifth grade. The theme will be "Code: Jesus." 
</P>
<P>
 Cost is $20 per person and scholarships are available. The church is at 30071 
Ivy Glenn Drive. Information: (714) 249-1218. 
</P>
<P>
 A series of four free workshops on conflict resolution will be offered at 
University United Methodist Church in Irvine. The workshop tomorrow is on the 
topic "Domestic Conflict: Problems and Possibilities in Family Disputes." Next 
week the topic is "Conflict in the Community: Identifying and Responding to 
Local Tensions." 
</P>
<P>
 The workshops are on Sundays from 4 to 6 p.m. in the Fellowship Hall at the 
church, 18422 Culver Drive. For more information, call Chris Whytock at (714) 
668-6214 or the church office at (714) 786-8354. 
</P>
<P>
 St. Clement's By The Sea Episcopal Church in San Clemente will host an art 
exhibit of works by Yevgeniy V. Zolotsev today at noon. He became a member of 
the Union of Free Artists in St. Petersburg in 1989 and has displayed his work 
both in his native Russia as well as Germany, Finland and the United States. He 
immigrated to this country in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
 The exhibition is at 190 Avenida Aragon. Information: (714) 492-3401. 
</P>
<P>
 The Center for Spiritual Development in Orange will offer a Holistic Retreat 
for one week beginning Aug. 5. 
</P>
<P>
 Cost for private room and board is $325, shared room and board is $310. 
Registration for the retreat is required by Wednesday. The Center is at 434 S. 
Batavia St. Information: (714) 744-3175. 
</P>
<P>
 Galen F. Hertweck will be installed as pastor of Family Christian Center in 
Lake Forest on Sunday during the 10 a.m. worship service. He served as pastor 
of King's Chapel Christian Center in Springfield, Mo., and has taught in 
colleges and seminaries in the United States, Europe and Pacific Rim countries. 
The Rev. T. Ray Rachels, district superintendent of the Southern California 
